'''''The View from Serendip''''' is a collection of essays and anecdotes by [[Arthur C. Clarke|Arthur&nbsp;C. Clarke]], first published in 1977. The pieces include Clarke's experiences with diving,  [[Sri Lanka]], his relationships with other science fiction authors such as [[Isaac Asimov]], and other personal memoirs. There are also reproductions of past lectures, as well as speculations about things of scientific interest.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clarke |first=Arthur C. |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/arthur-c-clarke/view-from-serendip/ |title=THE VIEW FROM SERENDIP by Arthur C. Clarke |publisher=Kirkus Reviews |date=17 October 1977 |accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref> The essay "The World of 2001" had been previously published in [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]. It predicted the end of menial labor (mental as well as manual), due to [[automation]] and bio-engineered apes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/mar/22/robot-jobs-humans-used-to-do-fight-back |title=When robots take our jobs, humans will be the new 1%. Here's how to fight back &#124; Michael Belfiore &#124; Opinion |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref> 
 
